01:09:39.729 --> 01:09:43.170
So let me just end with
Black-Scholes.

01:09:43.170 --> 01:09:48.420
So in 1972 Black and Scholes
wrote a famous paper.

01:09:48.420 --> 01:09:49.720
And what did they do?
 

01:09:49.720 --> 01:09:52.939
They started off by saying,
this model we had,

01:09:52.939 --> 01:09:56.909
you see, of the stock market
which follows a geometric random

01:09:56.909 --> 01:09:58.609
walk,
it can go up by a certain

01:09:58.609 --> 01:10:00.670
percentage or down by a certain
percentage.

01:10:00.670 --> 01:10:02.479
We've used that with interest
rates too.

01:10:02.479 --> 01:10:05.078
They can go up or down by a
certain percentage.

01:10:05.078 --> 01:10:08.109
Here the stocks can go up or
down by a certain percentage.

01:10:08.109 --> 01:10:11.738
We saw that you could solve
models like that very easily.

01:10:11.738 --> 01:10:14.591
So Black and Scholes,
Fischer Black who is a great

01:10:14.591 --> 01:10:17.618
economist, and Myron Scholes who
won the Nobel Prize,

01:10:17.618 --> 01:10:20.470
but was not as mathematical as
Fischer Black.

01:10:20.470 --> 01:10:23.100
Anyway, he started the hedge
fund Long Term Capital.

01:10:23.100 --> 01:10:25.538
Myron Scholes was one of the
people.

01:10:25.538 --> 01:10:30.506
They looked in 1972 at the
returns each day on the S&amp;P

01:10:30.506 --> 01:10:34.078
500, and they binned them up
like this.

01:10:34.078 --> 01:10:37.903
So here are the number of times
the return was between .47

01:10:37.903 --> 01:10:40.050
percent and some other number.
 

01:10:40.050 --> 01:10:43.319
And then they compared that to
a normally distributed random

01:10:43.319 --> 01:10:46.699
variable, and look how close to
normally distributed it is.

01:10:46.699 --> 01:10:47.689
It's practically like that.
 

01:10:47.689 --> 01:10:51.220
So this thing over here is
exactly normally distributed,

01:10:51.220 --> 01:10:55.189
and this is the frequency graph
of what actually happened that

01:10:55.189 --> 01:10:57.122
year,
incredibly close to normally

01:10:57.122 --> 01:10:57.779
distributed.
 

01:10:57.779 --> 01:11:00.386
If you take the cumulative
occurrence of each thing and

01:11:00.386 --> 01:11:03.430
compare it to the normal it's
incredibly close to the normal.

01:11:03.430 --> 01:11:05.978
So they said, "Gosh,
isn't it great,

01:11:05.978 --> 01:11:09.211
this model of things going up
or down by a certain percentage

01:11:09.211 --> 01:11:11.002
every year,
maybe with a drift,

01:11:11.002 --> 01:11:14.109
that's exactly the model the
stock market seems to follow,

01:11:14.109 --> 01:11:17.442
and maybe interest rates follow
that sort of model too,"

01:11:17.442 --> 01:11:20.328
and that's why we've worked
with all those models.

01:11:20.328 --> 01:11:24.863
Well, it turns out if you make
those assumptions and then you

01:11:24.863 --> 01:11:29.095
try to solve for option prices
you can do it very quickly

01:11:29.095 --> 01:11:32.488
through some formula,
which I'm not going to have

01:11:32.488 --> 01:11:33.390
time to present.
 

01:11:33.390 --> 01:11:36.069
It'll only take one minute,
but I'm going to skip that.

01:11:36.069 --> 01:11:37.319
So what happened then?
 

01:11:37.319 --> 01:11:41.380
So this was the second high
point of, you know,

01:11:41.380 --> 01:11:46.500
there's the CAPM model and then
the Black-Scholes model.

01:11:46.500 --> 01:11:49.350
You've done problems with
Black-Scholes now in the problem

01:11:49.350 --> 01:11:51.698
set to figure out the value of a
call option.

01:11:51.698 --> 01:11:54.484
So I'm just pointing out that
you could put it in a spread

01:11:54.484 --> 01:11:56.880
sheet like I've done,
which will be on the web.

01:11:56.880 --> 01:12:01.100
And you can do daily returns,
and fix the standard deviation

01:12:01.100 --> 01:12:03.289
and stuff,
and do backward induction

01:12:03.289 --> 01:12:05.617
incredibly quickly,
and figure out the value of the

01:12:05.617 --> 01:12:07.819
call option,
even get a closed form formula

01:12:07.819 --> 01:12:10.234
for it,
and then explain why call

01:12:10.234 --> 01:12:13.470
option prices have the form that
they do.

01:12:13.470 --> 01:12:15.860
So it was a great triumph and
it relied on things being

01:12:15.860 --> 01:12:16.880
normally distributed.
 

01:12:16.880 --> 01:12:18.710
I'm down to 30 seconds.
 

01:12:18.710 --> 01:12:21.328
So what happened?
 

01:12:21.328 --> 01:12:25.713
If you do the same thing
recently--so you do exactly the

01:12:25.713 --> 01:12:30.097
same thing and bin everything up
like Fischer Black did,

01:12:30.097 --> 01:12:32.408
not in 1972--shit,
sorry.

01:12:32.408 --> 01:12:35.902
Not in 1972 but the last five
years, say, they only did one

01:12:35.902 --> 01:12:37.890
year, but you do the last five.
 

01:12:37.890 --> 01:12:40.753
Actually I did this a couple
years ago, so from seven years

01:12:40.753 --> 01:12:41.890
ago to two years ago.
 

01:12:41.890 --> 01:12:44.863
If the pink thing is normally
distributed and we do the same

01:12:44.863 --> 01:12:46.779
binning that Black and Scholes
did,

01:12:46.779 --> 01:12:50.072
look everyday at what the
return is and stick it in a bin

01:12:50.072 --> 01:12:53.350
and just do the frequency thing,
what do you see?

01:12:53.350 --> 01:12:57.378
You see that there are a lot
more times where in reality the

01:12:57.378 --> 01:13:00.766
move was very small,
but there are a lot more times

01:13:00.766 --> 01:13:03.189
in reality where the move was
very big.

01:13:03.189 --> 01:13:06.920
So this is precisely what you
call a fat tail,

01:13:06.920 --> 01:13:10.162
that you get smaller moves than
the normally distributed ones

01:13:10.162 --> 01:13:13.350
but also bigger moves than the
normally distributed ones.

01:13:13.350 --> 01:13:14.810
So you can have some big
negative moves.

01:13:14.810 --> 01:13:17.939
And so we know we've had some
huge negative shocks.

01:13:17.939 --> 01:13:22.703
So I'm ending now with this
thought that finance produced

01:13:22.703 --> 01:13:26.894
